For what it's worth, you're not alone in that hole – it can depreciating, especially when you see popular writers swear they'll be more vocal, only to seemingly vanish when there's no praise to be reaped for themselves on their downtime. But that aside, as advised by the other anon, it's good to put yourself out there; more eyes on your work means more opportunities to hear fresh takes from external sources. I strongly recommend placing express requests for feedback and commentary on your submissions somewhere before the body of your story. Sometimes, that can provide "permission" for readers who may be inherently nervous, or invite otherwise unscrupulous readers to take in your writing more critically, so they can more competently discuss their opinions in the comments section when they're finished. Otherwise, just persevere and hang in there; get your writer's mileage in, keep improving, and keep making something of your ideas. You're doing the hardest part just by getting a few paragraphs down every time you sit down to write – flair and technique will develop over time, as well time invested in personal study and experimental writing (Smiley is openly prolific about this practice, for example).
